<methodology slug="growth-brand-positioning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>Six-step positioning framework: target customer, competitive alternatives, unique differentiator, category strategy, positioning statement, and validation through customer interviews.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>positioning</tag>
      <tag>brand</tag>
      <tag>marketing</tag>
      <tag>differentiation</tag>
      <tag>gtm</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="growth-gtm-strategy"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Brand Positioning</title>

    <summary>A six-step framework for owning a specific position in a target customer's mind: define the customer ruthlessly precisely, map competitive alternatives, identify a single "only we" differentiator, choose a category strategy, craft an internal positioning statement plus one-liner, and validate through customer interviews. Uses April Dunford's methodology as the primary anchor.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Without explicit positioning, prospects evaluate on price and features — a race to the bottom. Strong positioning disqualifies wrong-fit prospects by design, makes sales conversations shorter, and creates a durable competitive moat if the differentiator is non-trivial to copy. Weak positioning is the most common root cause of high CAC and low conversion.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New product or new market segment: derive positioning before writing any copy.</item>
        <item>Stale messaging: existing positioning blends with competitors or customers can't repeat it.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch stress-test: validate a positioning statement against competitive alternatives and customer interviews.</item>
        <item>Sales/marketing alignment: produce the messaging hierarchy (one-liner → elevator pitch → 3 key messages → proof points).</item>
        <item>Category strategy decision: existing vs. sub-category vs. new category with explicit tradeoffs.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Tactical copy production (headlines, ad copy, email subjects) — positioning is upstream input, not copy itself.</item>
        <item>Brand identity (logo, palette, typography) — different domain.</item>
        <item>Personas from scratch — use persona-building methodology; positioning consumes personas.</item>
        <item>Competitive intelligence on individual rivals — use growth-competitor-analysis; positioning consumes that output.</item>
        <item>Repositioning a public-company brand under shareholder scrutiny — beyond methodology scope.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="step-1-define-target-customer">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Be ruthlessly specific about the target customer: name role, company type and stage, goal, and obstacle. "Businesses" or "developers" is not a target customer.</statement>
        <rationale>Positioning that resonates with everyone resonates with no one. A specific target customer description disqualifies wrong-fit prospects by design, which is a feature not a bug — it raises conversion among fit buyers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad" title="Broad target customer">
        <note>Target customer: "Businesses who want to grow their revenue." No role, no company type, no situation, no obstacle — every B2B product could claim this.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Specific target customer">
        <note>Target customer: "Marketing manager at a Series A SaaS startup who is trying to increase trial-to-paid conversion but struggles with limited engineering resources." Role + company type + goal + obstacle.</note>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/positioning-canvas.md">Positioning canvas template including target customer section</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-map-competitive-alternatives">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>List at least 3 competitive alternatives including: direct competitors, indirect competitors, the status quo (doing nothing), and substitutes (DIY, hire someone). Frame positioning against this list explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>Customers always frame their decision against alternatives. Owning the framing prevents competitors from defining it. Without alternatives, positioning cannot be differentiated — "X is the Y" has no meaning without "unlike Z".</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-find-your-only">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Identify the one thing only your product can claim: a unique feature, approach, focus, expertise level, experience quality, proven result metric, or ecosystem integration. Pick one; more than one dilutes the claim.</statement>
        <rationale>Multi-pillar positioning is forgettable. Single-pillar positioning compounds over 12+ months into recognition. Competitors can copy features; they cannot easily copy a proven result tied to a specific methodology or a deep ecosystem integration.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-category-strategy">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Choose one of four category strategies: existing category (easiest to understand), sub-category (differentiate in crowded market), new category (create a space), or versus (challenger positioning). Only create a new category if you can fund market education for 2+ years.</statement>
        <rationale>Category creation looks attractive but creates an extra job: educating the market about a problem space before selling the solution. Most early-stage products should use sub-category framing to inherit existing search demand while carving a distinct niche.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-craft-positioning-statement">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write the internal positioning statement in this form: "For [target customer] who [situation/need], [Product] is the [category] that [key benefit], unlike [alternatives] we [unique differentiator]."</statement>
        <rationale>This structure forces explicit answers to all five positioning questions simultaneously and surfaces gaps (vague differentiator, undefined category) that prose descriptions hide.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Well-structured positioning statement">
        <note>Internal statement: "For solo SaaS founders who want to ship faster without a team, Faion Network is the AI development framework that provides proven methodologies and AI agents, unlike courses or just tools, we combine education with working software." External one-liner: "Faion Network helps solo founders ship products 10x faster with AI agents and proven methodologies."</note>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/messaging-hierarchy.md">Messaging hierarchy template for external communication</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="step-6-validate">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Test positioning by asking customers to describe you to a peer. If they invent their own version, the positioning is not sticking. Test with 5+ customers before treating it as stable.</statement>
        <rationale>Internal positioning that sounds sharp often dissolves in the field. Customer language is the ground truth for whether positioning actually transferred.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-positioning-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Target audience too broad ("businesses", "developers" without qualifiers).</description>
        <reason>Message resonates with no one; sales conversions remain low despite high traffic because wrong-fit buyers are not disqualified.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Feature-based positioning ("we have X feature").</description>
        <reason>Features are easily copied within one product cycle. Position on value, approach, or outcome — things that take more than 6 months to replicate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Claiming too many differentiators at once.</description>
        <reason>Multi-pillar positioning is forgettable. Customers compress to one thing in their memory; let them compress to the thing you want them to remember.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Inside-out thinking: leading with features instead of customer problems.</description>
        <reason>Customers care about their goals and obstacles, not the product's architecture. Positioning must start from customer situation language.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Changing positioning within 12 months without a significant product or market reason.</description>
        <reason>Brand recognition requires repetition. Frequent pivots prevent any single positioning from accumulating recognition in the market.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="before-after-examples">
      <example type="bad" title="Developer tool weak positioning">
        <note>Developer tool weak positioning: "A modern code editor for developers." No target customer, no differentiator, no alternative framing — every editor in the market could claim this.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Developer tool strong positioning">
        <note>Developer tool strong positioning: "For developers who hate context switching, Cursor is the AI-first code editor that understands your entire codebase, unlike VS Code or Copilot alone, we make AI your pair programmer, not just autocomplete." Specific trigger (context switching), specific alternative (VS Code + Copilot), specific differentiator (full-codebase understanding vs. token-level autocomplete).</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="SaaS analytics weak positioning">
        <note>SaaS analytics weak positioning: "Analytics for your business." No audience, no competitive frame, no differentiator.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="SaaS analytics strong positioning">
        <note>SaaS analytics strong positioning: "For bootstrapped founders who need insights without data science, Plausible is the privacy-friendly analytics that shows what matters in under 60 seconds, unlike Google Analytics, we're simple, fast, and GDPR-compliant out of the box." Audience (bootstrapped founders), trigger (no data science), differentiator (speed + privacy + compliance).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-gotchas">
      <p>Methodology assumes the team has done customer interviews; without that input, agents will hallucinate target-customer pain. "Find your only" exercise often produces fake uniqueness if research is thin — small teams claim differentiators competitors trivially also have. Category creation guidance is brief; the failure mode (creating a category nobody searches for) is real and harder than the doc implies. Positioning maps (2x2 grids) bias toward two axes; multi-dimensional differentiation is hard to render and hard to communicate. Doesn't cover repositioning during pivots — different psychological/customer-trust dynamics. B2B-leaning frame; B2C consumer-brand positioning often hinges on emotional/identity vectors barely addressed.</p>
      <p>Best practices: Interview customers in their words first; positioning written without verbatim language reads as marketing-team folklore. Disqualify prospects on purpose — strong positioning shrinks the addressable market by design and lifts conversion among fit. Pick one differentiator and over-invest in it for 12+ months; multi-pillar positioning is forgettable. Frame against alternatives explicitly ("unlike X, we Y"); customers always frame against alternatives, so own the framing. Test the positioning by asking customers to describe you to a peer — if they invent their own version, your positioning isn't sticking. Track competitor homepage diffs monthly; if a competitor moves toward your space, escalate to a positioning review. Keep an internal positioning doc separate from customer-facing one-liner; the internal doc is denser and covers tradeoffs. Only create a new category if you can fund market education for 2+ years; otherwise use sub-category framing.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs default to category-defining puffery: "the leading platform", "the most powerful solution".</description>
        <reason>Superlatives are unverifiable and unconvincing. Force the agent to replace every superlative with a concrete proof point tied to a named metric or customer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents conflate features with differentiators when generating positioning.</description>
        <reason>Run a follow-up pass: "Can a competitor ship this in 6 months? If yes, it is a feature, not positioning." Differentiators must have structural defensibility.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Positioning generated without verbatim customer-language input reads as bland and inside-out.</description>
        <reason>Block synthesis until customer interview quotes are in context. Agents hallucinate target-customer pain when research inputs are absent.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Competitive analysis from web scraping captures stated positioning, not actual market perception.</description>
        <reason>Layer in review-site sentiment. Auto-generated category names are often unsearchable nonsense ("Revenue Intelligence Cloud Platform"); validate against Google search volume and analyst categories. Messaging hierarchies will drift if regenerated each cycle — maintain the hierarchy in version control and amend, don't recreate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents over-cite Dunford / Crossing the Chasm / Ries-Trout without distinguishing when each applies.</description>
        <reason>Crossing the Chasm is for early-market enterprise tech, not consumer SaaS. Translation/localization: positioning that works in English often fails when literally translated — re-do the canvas per language market.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Sequence: (1) research agent gathers customer interview transcripts + competitor pages + review-site data, (2) synthesizer agent produces draft positioning canvas, (3) validator agent runs Dunford-style check (is it specific? is it grounded in real alternatives? does it own one differentiator?), (4) human refines, (5) agent rolls forward to messaging hierarchy and Wynter-style preference tests. Pair with growth-gtm-strategy, research/market-researcher, comms/communicator.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: general-purpose Claude subagent for Dunford "Obviously Awesome" validator pass against the canvas. Source: Dunford positioning validator on draft canvas. Check: (1) is target customer specific enough to disqualify wrong-fit prospects? (2) is the unique value something competitors literally cannot claim? (3) is the category choice intentional and defended? (4) would a customer repeat this positioning back accurately? Output: per-question pass/fail + improvement suggestion. Given customer interview snippets, extract: exact phrases customers use for the problem, alternatives they considered or use today, top 2 emotional drivers, top 2 functional drivers, objections to current solutions. Do not paraphrase — keep customer language verbatim.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/positioning-canvas.md" purpose="Full positioning canvas with target customer, alternatives, capabilities, proof points, statement, one-liner"/>
      <template path="templates/messaging-hierarchy.md" purpose="Messaging hierarchy: one-liner, elevator pitch, 3 key messages, proof points, vocabulary"/>
      <template path="templates/canvas-validator.py" purpose="Dunford-style canvas validator: flags broad target, too few alternatives, too many differentiators"/>
    </templates>

